data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed you to opt into **sync-over-async** (e.g., via `ConfigureWarnings` or a Cosmos-specific option) so that synchronous LINQ operators like `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` would silently block on the underlying async calls.

**In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed.** The Cosmos DB provider now **throws `InvalidOperationException` at runtime** for all synchronous query and save operations — with no workaround. The Cosmos SDK only exposes async APIs, and EF Core no longer wraps them with blocking calls.

Every method in your repository will throw. The fix is to go fully async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
| Sync (broken in .NET 11) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through all callers (controllers, services, etc.). Remove the old sync-over-async opt-in from your `DbContext` configuration — it will fail to compile or be silently ignored.
